 ----------------------------------------- C# Basics -----------------------------------------
1)What Is C#.
->C# (C-Sharp) is a programming language developed by Microsoft that runs on the .NET Framework.
->C# is used to develop web apps, desktop apps, mobile apps, games and much more.

2)What is C# Data Types (Value & References type).
->Value Types->Value types store the actual data directly in memory.
When you assign a value type variable to another variable, a copy of the value is created.
-Stored on the stack (mostly)
-Each variable has its own copy of data
-Changes in one variable do not affect another                  
Examples:
int
float
double
decimal
bool
char
struct
enum

->Reference Types->Reference types store a reference (memory address) to the actual data, not the data itself.
When you assign a reference type variable to another variable, both point to the same object in memory.
-Stored on the heap`
-Variables share the same memory reference
Examples:
class
string
array
object
interface
delegate


3)What is C# Literals?
->In C#, a literal is a fixed value written directly in the source code.
Literals represent constant values that do not change during program execution.
Types of C# Literals
Integer Literals
Floating-Point Literals
Character Literals
String Literals
Boolean Literals
Null Literal

4)What is Type Casting?
->Type Casting is the process of explicitly converting one data type into another using a cast operator.
  It is mainly used when data loss may occur.

Type Conversion?
-Implicit Conversion (Automatic)->int a = 10;
double b = a;   // Implicit conversion
-Explicit Conversion (Manual)->double x = 25.75;
int y = (int)x;   // Explicit conversion


4)What is C# Variable & Constant
->A variable in C# is a named memory location used to store data that can change during program execution.
Syntax->dataType variableName = value;
->A constant in C# is a fixed value whose value cannot be changed once it is assigned.
->Value cannot be modified
  Declared using the const keyword
  Must be assigned at declaration time
Syntax->const dataType constantName = value;

5)what is C# Operators?
->1ï¸âƒ£ Arithmetic Operators->Used to perform mathematical calculations.
   | Operator | Meaning             | Example |
| -------- | ------------------- | ------- |
| `+`      | Addition            | `a + b` |
| `-`      | Subtraction         | `a - b` |
| `*`      | Multiplication      | `a * b` |
| `/`      | Division            | `a / b` |
| `%`      | Modulus (remainder) | `a % b` |

2ï¸âƒ£ Logical Operators->Used to combine conditions and return true or false.
| Operator | Meaning     |   
| -------- | ----------- | 
| `&&`     | Logical AND |         
| `||'     | Logical OR  |
| `!`      | Logical NOT |   

3ï¸âƒ£ Bitwise Operators->Used to perform operations at the binary (bit) level.
| Operator | Meaning     |            
| -------- | ----------- | 
| `&`      | Bitwise AND |            
| `||`     |  Bitwise OR |
| `^`      | Bitwise XOR |            
| `~`      | Bitwise NOT |            
| `<<`     | Left Shift  |            
| `>>`     | Right Shift |            

4ï¸âƒ£ Ternary Operator->Used as a short form of if-else.
condition ? value_if_true : value_if_false;

6)C# Control Flow Statements
-Control flow statements in C# are used to control the order in which program statements are executed based on conditions or repetition.
1ï¸âƒ£ if Statement->Executes code only when a condition is true.
2ï¸âƒ£ ifâ€“else Statement->Executes one block if the condition is true, otherwise executes the else block.
3ï¸âƒ£ elseâ€“if Ladder->Used to check multiple conditions.
4ï¸âƒ£ switch Statement->Used to select one option from many choices based on a value.
5ï¸âƒ£ Loops->Loops are used to repeat code multiple times.
   ðŸ”¹ for Loop->Used when the number of iterations is known.
   ðŸ”¹ while Loop->Executes while the condition is true.
   ðŸ”¹ doâ€“while Loop->Executes at least once, then checks the condition.
   ðŸ”¹ foreach Loop->Used to iterate over collections like arrays or lists.

----------------------------------------------Function & Methods---------------------------------------------------
1)What is Method Declaration & Invocation?
--Method Declaration 
-A method declaration defines a method by specifying its name, return type, parameters, and body.
It tells the compiler what the method will do.
--Method Invocation
-A method invocation means calling or executing a method to perform its defined task.

2)What is Method Overloading?
-Method Overloading in C# means having multiple methods with the same name in the same class but with different parameters is called to Method Overloading.
-The compiler decides which method to call based on the number, type, or order of parameters.

3)What is User-Defined Function?
-A user-defined function is a function created by the programmer to perform a specific task.
It helps in reusing code, improving readability, and reducing repetition.
-Types of User-Defined Functions
  No parameter, no return value
  With parameter, no return value
  No parameter, with return value
  With parameter, with return value

4)What Call by Value & Call by Reference (ref, out, in)?
-Call by Value â†’ Copy of value
ref â†’ Reference (read & write)
out â†’ Output value
in â†’ Read-only reference

5)What is Recursion?
->Recursion is a programming technique in which a method calls itself to solve a problem.
It continues until a base condition is met to stop the recursive calls.

6)What is Named & Optional Parameters?
->Named parameters allow you to pass arguments to a method by specifying the parameter name, so the order of parameters does not matter.
->Optional parameters are parameters that have default values.
If no value is passed during method call, the default value is used automatically.

7)What is Params Array?
->A params array in C# allows a method to accept a variable number of arguments as a single parameter.
It is declared using the params keyword.
-Params Array Means Variable number of arguments.
-Purpose Flexibility & cleaner code.


---------------------------------------------User Interaction --------------------------------------------------------
1)What is User Input (Console.ReadLine)?
->User input in C# means taking data from the user at runtime.
Console.ReadLine() is used to read a line of text entered by the user from the console.

2)What is Output (Console.WriteLine)?
->Console.WriteLine() is used to print text or values on the console and then move the cursor to the next line.

3)What is Command Line Argument?
->A command line argument is a value passed to a program when it starts running from the command prompt or terminal.
In C#, command line arguments are received using the Main(string[] args) parameter.

4)What is String Formatting & String Interpolation?
->String formatting is a way to insert values into a string using placeholders like {0}, {1}, etc.
->String interpolation is a modern and cleaner way to embed variables directly inside a string using $"".


