2)What is Nullable Types in C#?
->Nullable types in C# allow value types (like int, bool, DateTime) to store null values.
They are useful when a variable may not have a value.

Short Syntax (?)
int? age = null;
bool? isActive = true;

Long Syntax
Nullable<int> marks = null;


3)What is String Operations in C#?
->String operations in C# are methods and techniques used to manipulate strings, such as creating, modifying, comparing, searching, and formatting text data.
  string first = "Hello";
  string second = "World";
  string result = first + " " + second;

  string name = "Rahul";
  Console.WriteLine(name.Length);   // 5

  string text = "CSharp";
  string part = text.Substring(1, 3);  // Sha

  string msg = "Hello World";
  string newMsg = msg.Replace("World", "C#");

  string name = "Manan";
  Console.WriteLine(name.ToUpper());
  Console.WriteLine(name.ToLower());

  string data = "  Hello  ";
  Console.WriteLine(data.Trim());

  string email = "test@gmail.com";

  email.Contains("@");
  email.StartsWith("test");
  email.EndsWith(".com");

  string line = "A,B,C";
  string[] values = line.Split(',');

  string a = "Hello";
  string b = "hello";
  bool equal = a.Equals(b, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase);

  string name = "Rahul";
  int age = 25
  Console.WriteLine($"Name: {name}, Age: {age}");


4)What is StringBuilder?
->StringBuilder is a class in C# used to create and modify strings efficiently without creating new string objects every time.
It is useful when string data changes frequently.

using System.Text;
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
sb.Append("Hello");
sb.Append(" ");
sb.Append("World");
Console.WriteLine(sb.ToString());
->Common StringBuilder Methods
Append()
AppendLine()
Insert()
Remove()
Replace()
Clear()

5)Constant (const) vs ReadOnly (readonly) in C#?
->const (Constant)
  A constant is a variable whose value is fixed at compile time and cannot be changed ever.
->readonly
  A readonly variable is a field whose value can be assigned only once, either at declaration time or inside a constructor, and cannot be modified afterward.

6)What is C# Properties: Auto, Backed & Expression-Bodied?
->Property (General)
  A property in C# is a member that provides controlled access to a class field using get and set accessors.
->Auto-Implemented Property
  An auto property is a property where the compiler automatically creates the backing field.
  It is used when no extra logic is needed in get/set.

->Backed Property
  A backed property (backing-field property) uses a private field to store the value and allows custom logic in get/set.

->Expression-Bodied Property
  An expression-bodied property is a short, concise syntax for properties that return a single expression.

1ï¸âƒ£ Auto-Implemented Property
   Example
   class Student
   {
    public int Age { get; set; }
    }
2ï¸âƒ£ Backed Property (Private Field)
    Example
    class Student
    {
    private int _age;
    public int Age
    {
        get { return _age; }
        set
        {
            if (value > 0)
                _age = value;
        }
     }
    }
3ï¸âƒ£ Expression-Bodied Property
class Student
{
    public string FirstName { get; set; }
    public string LastName { get; set; }

    public string FullName => $"{FirstName} {LastName}";
}

7)Stack vs Heap Memory (C#)?
| Feature      |  Stack Memory| Heap Memory            |
| ------------ | ------------ | ---------------------- |
| Storage      | Value types  | Reference types        |
| Allocation   | Automatic    | Dynamic                |
| Deallocation | Automatic    | Garbage Collector      |
| Speed        | Fast         | Slower                 |
| Size         | Limited      | Large                  |
| Lifetime     | Method scope | Application controlled |
| Access       | Direct       | Reference-based        |


8)Boxing & Unboxing in C#?
->Boxing is the process of converting a value type into a reference type (object).
The value is wrapped inside an object and stored on the heap.

-Unboxing is the process of extracting the value type from the object back into its original value type.

9)Exception Handling in C# (try, catch, finally, throw)?
->Exception handling in C# is a mechanism used to handle runtime errors gracefully so that the program does not crash and continues execution in a controlled manner.
1ï¸âƒ£ try Block-> The try block contains code that may cause an exception during program execution.
2ï¸âƒ£ catch Block->The catch block handles the exception thrown in the try block and allows the program to continue execution.
3ï¸âƒ£ finally Block->The finally block contains code that is always executed, whether an exception occurs or not.
4ï¸âƒ£ throw Keyword->The throw keyword is used to explicitly generate an exception in a program.

10)Enum & Struct in C#?
->An enum is a value type that is used to define a set of named constant values, which makes the code more readable and meaningful.
Struct->A struct is a value type in C# used to group related variables of different data types into a single unit.

Enum (Enumeration)
enum Day
{
    Monday,
    Tuesday,
    Wednesday,
    Thursday,
    Friday
}
how to use
Day today = Day.Monday;
Struct
struct Employee
{
    public int Id;
    public string Name;
}
how to use
Employee emp;
emp.Id = 1;
emp.Name = "Rahul";

One-Line Summary
Enum â†’ Fixed named constants
Struct â†’ Small grouped data


-----------------------------------------------Object-Oriented Programming(oop)------------------------------------------------
1)What Is The Oops and difference Between Functional & Object Oritend Programming Langauge?
->OOPs is a programming style where a program is built using objects that contain data and functions.
->Object-oriented programming is a programming style where programs are created using classes and objects.
OOPs 4 Pillars
Encapsulation
Abstraction
Inheritance
Polymorphism
Functional programming is a programming style where programs are written using functions and data does not change.
| Feature             | Functional Programming | Object-Oriented Programming |
| ------------------- | ---------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Focus               | Functions              | Objects                     |
| Data                | Immutable              | Mutable                     |
| State               | Avoids state           | Uses state                  |
| Code style          | Declarative            | Imperative                  |
| Reusability         | Function reuse         | Class & inheritance         |
| Real-world modeling | Difficult              | Easy                        |
| Examples            | F#, Haskell            | C#, Java                    |

2)What Is Class & Objects?
->class->A class is a blueprint or template that defines the properties (data/fields) and methods (behavior/functions) for objects.
  It does not occupy memory until an object is created.
  Think of it as a design or plan for an entity.

->object->An object is a real-world instance of a class.
  It contains actual data in memory.
  Objects have state (properties) and behavior (methods) as defined in their class.

3)What Is Constructor & Destructors?
->A constructor is a special method in a class that is automatically called when an object is created.
->It is used to initialize objects and set default values.
->Constructor name must be the same as the class name.
->No return type, not even void.
Types Of Constructor
Default Constructor->Called automatically when no constructor is defined.
Parameterized Constructor->Allows passing values during object creation.
Static Constructor->Used to initialize static members of the class. Called once automatically when the class is loaded.
                    Cannot take parameters.
Copy Constructor->A Copy Constructor is a constructor that creates a new object by copying the data of an existing object of the same class.
C# does not provide a built-in copy constructor, but you can create your own.'

this Keyword in C#->The this keyword in C# refers to the current instance of the class.

Destuctors




